          "body": "The chapter opens with one of the most arresting images in all of prophetic literature: Judah's sin is not written in pencil on the surface of behavior, erasable by a brief reform. It is inscribed with an iron stylus and a diamond point on the tablet of the heart and on the horns of the altars (17:1). The heart-tablet metaphor deliberately inverts the new covenant promise of Jeremiah 31:33, where the LORD vows to write His Torah on the heart of His people. Here, the covenant has been reversed: what is written on Judah's heart is not the law of God but the record of transgression. The high places on green hills (17:2-3) are not incidental to the indictment — they are generational worship sites the children memorize the way they memorize their parents' names (17:2). Idolatry has become domestic, habitual, transmitted. The judgment that follows (17:3-4) is proportionate: the wealth and treasures laid up through covenantal unfaithfulness will become plunder; the inheritance the LORD gave will be relinquished; the people will serve enemies in an unknown land. The phrase 'you will, even of yourself, let go of your inheritance' (17:4) is striking — the exile is not merely imposed from outside; it is the natural outcome of a trust that has already abandoned God. The fire kindled in the LORD's anger burns forever (17:4) — judgment proportionate to sin that has been engraved, not sketched."
